 for paraneoplastic syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following represents the correct sequence of investigations for renal tumours?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diagnosis: CT Abdomen and Pelvis with IV contrast; Extent: CXR, bone scan, liver CT; Paraneoplastic: calcium, FBE, ESR","Diagnosis: calcium, FBE, ESR; Extent: CXR, bone scan, liver CT; Paraneoplastic: CT Abdomen and Pelvis with IV contrast","Diagnosis: CXR, bone scan, liver CT; Extent: CT Abdomen and Pelvis with IV contrast; Paraneoplastic: calcium, FBE, ESR","Diagnosis: CT Abdomen and Pelvis with IV contrast; Extent: calcium, FBE, ESR; Paraneoplastic: CXR, bone scan, liver CT","Diagnosis: calcium, FBE, ESR; Extent: CT Abdomen and Pelvis with IV contrast; Paraneoplastic: CXR, bone scan, liver CT"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of investigations for renal tumours is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT Abdomen and Pelvis with intravenous contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary diagnostic tool for renal tumours as it provides detailed imaging of the kidneys and surrounding structures\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDisease extent is assessed using \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray, bone scan, and liver CT\u003C/strong\u003E to identify potential metastases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EParaneoplastic syndromes are evaluated using \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium levels, full blood examination, and erythrocyte sedimentation rate\u003C/strong\u003E to detect systemic effects of the tumour\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe other sequences incorrectly mix the diagnostic, staging, and paraneoplastic investigations\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Renal tumours are diagnosed primarily using CT with intravenous contrast","Extent of disease is assessed using chest X-ray, bone scan, and liver imaging","Paraneoplastic effects are evaluated using calcium levels, full blood examination, and erythrocyte sedimentation rate"],"references":["Rose TL, Kim WY. Renal Cell Carcinoma: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Sep 24;332(12):1001-1010. doi: 10.1001/jama.2024.12848. PMID: 39196544.","Gray RE, Harris GT. Renal Cell Carcinoma: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Feb 1;99(3):179-184. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2019 Jun 15;99(12):732. PMID: 30702258.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15079"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:18:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:20:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7767"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links"